item.dc:creator: anthonyhua
item.content:encoded:
This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:

Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like piña coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)

...or something like this:

The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.

As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!

item.title: Privacy Policy
item.dc:creator: anthonyhua
item.content:encoded:
Who we are

Suggested text: Our website address is: https://cs272-wordpress.cs.wisc.edu/f24/ahua7.

Comments

Suggested text: When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor’s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.

An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.

Media

Suggested text: If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.

Cookies

Suggested text: If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.

If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.

When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select "Remember Me", your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.

If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.

Embedded content from other websites

Suggested text: Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.

These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.

Who we share your data with

Suggested text: If you request a password reset, your IP address will be included in the reset email.

How long we retain your data

Suggested text: If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.

For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.

What rights you have over your data

Suggested text: If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.

Where your data is sent

Suggested text: Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.

item.dc:creator: anthonyhua
item.content:encoded:
For a bite-sized summary, you can download my resume here

They say college is a place where you plant seeds. While at the University of Redlands, I planted three:

STEM

I pursued a Bachelors of Science in Chemistry and had opportunity to do a research project on the topics of Environmental Chemistry and Microbiology.

Mentorship

I was heavily involved in Students Together Empowering Peers (STEP), a mentorship program that helped first-gen students of color transition into college and adult life. Along these lines, I also worked as a Peer Tutor, and assisted students in Gen and Organic Chemistry.

Libraries

I worked as a Student Assistant at my University's Library. This was a front desk role that leveraged my long history in and love of customer service. I was eventually promoted to a Student Lead position, which allowed me to take on project-based work, and leadership roles.

Majoring in Chemistry wasn't the best choice for natural way of thinking, but it did teach me value lessons:

  • The Path of Most Resistance:
  • The Strength of Diverse Expertise:
  • The Strength of Diverse Minds:

Being a person who wears my heart on my sleeve, I've was more drawn to my extracurricular. It was here that I learned the concept of "look for the helpers": that resources are always available and that we have a responsibility to guide those who were never taught how to find them.

Education

Bachelors of Science - Chemistry

University of Redlands

2016 to 2020

Thesis: Biodegradation of 4-nonylphenol isomers via Pseudomonas bacteria in Palisades Glacier, CA

Masters of Arts -
Library and Information Studies

University of Wisconsin - Madison

2024 to current

Work Experience

Circulation Specialist / Student Supervisor
at University of Wisconsin Madison

  • Circ Suppport
  • Student Supervising

On-Call Library Assistant
at Springfield Public Library

As an on-call staff, I filled gaps in coverage to provide consistent services for our patrons. I supported day-to-day transactions, like circulating material and registering library cards while upholding and communicating library procedures. Catering to the needs of our community, I also guided and instructed patrons on essential, technology-based resources, like the use of online catalogs and computer software.

STEM Resource Center Support
at Lane Community College

The STEM Learning Zone is the department resource center located within the Math, Science, and Engineering (SME) department. I am proud to have served as part of the team that revitalized the center after it had closed during COVID and aided students as they transitioned back into an in-person learning environment. We achieved a culture of reliability and inclusivity to meet the needs of a new generation of learners.
On the day-to-day, this involved coordinating student workers and faculty to ensure staffing needs are met. I maintained study spaces, supported tutoring, and organized our unique collection of circulation material to provide equitable access to department resources. Following department and course policies, I also managed proctoring services to support learning accommodations and accessibility. While staffing the front desk, I proudly connected with the student body, faculty, and department administration to enhance learning outcomes and build a welcoming and inclusive community.

Math and Science Tutor
at Academic Achievement Center

In both an online and in-person environment, I mentored students between 6th and 12th grades by identifying learning strengths and building confidence in STEM. Tutored in the subjects: algebra, geometry, precalculus, calculus, statistics, chemistry, and physics.

item.title: About me
item.dc:creator: anthonyhua
item.content:encoded:
Anthony Hua

Assembled in Los Angeles, California

My name is Anthony. My parents got me and my twin sister at a bargain-- a buy one, get one free deal! I grew up

Although I grew up in a first-generation Asian American household, my parents were non-conforming to the "tiger" stereotype. They prioritized Buddhist values of kindness and compassion, over academic excellence. After growing up, I realize how essential this upbringing was to our values today. While our cousins became doctors, I'm proud of my family of civic helpers. My dad was a postal carrier and my mom a caretaker. My older sister the child behavioral therapist, my twin sister a middles school music teacher, and me a librarian.

Places I've Lived, Stuff I Have Done


Redlands, California

They say college is a place where you plant seeds. While at the University of Redlands, I planted three. (1) Social pressures pushed me to pursue STEM. Originally, the plan was to do pre-med with a double major in Biochemistry but was humbled pretty quickly into just a Chemistry degree. I still enjoyed the challenge and even got the opportunity to do a research project on the topics of Environmental Chemistry and Microbiology.

Being a person who wears my heart on my sleeve, I've was more drawn to my extracurriculars. (2) I was heavily involved in Students Together Empowering Peers (STEP), a mentorship program that helped first-gen students of color transition into college and adult life. It was here that I learned the concept of "look for the helpers": that resources are always available and that we have a responsibility to guide those who were never taught how to find them.

During my Junior year, I landed a student gig at my university's library. I was hoping for a chill desk job to give me time to catch up on homework. I ended up finding a community. Among the team was my friend, Will. While I was the boy scout that got promoted to Student Lead, he was a bit of a scoundrel-- initiating shenanigans at the front desk and left messages in the stacks as riddles for us to solve. Despite this, he was adored for his charm and his antics got me through the latter half of college.

He had dreams of being a librarian and publishing his own book. However, Will tragically and suddenly passed in November 2020. The legacy of his wit and heart being passed on to those that knew and loved him.

Interlude: Pandemic

I graduated in 2020. Globally, nothing of note happened during this time. Utilizing my Chemistry degree, I briefly worked at as a Lab Analyst in a small water testing company's Microbiology Department. I learned I was not a great bench chemist, breaking beakers instead of "Breaking Bad".

Being cooped inside have me plenty of time to reflect. I thought about my time in Redlands and the three seeds I planted: the challenges that came with STEM, the purpose derived from mentorship, and the community that flourished from libraries.

Eugene, Oregon


Very abruptly, I decided to move to Eugene, OR in Summer of 2021. There wasn't much of a planned lined up-- just a nice change of pace after the pandemic. But it was a huge gamble, especially given the fact that I did not have a job lined up. I faced housing scarcity and challenges adjusting to a new town.

Things changed when I landed a part-time job for a Instructional Support at Lane Community College (LCC). The goals in this position was the rebuild a new iteration of STEM Resource Center that catered to students returning from years in online learning. The vision we had was to serve as the "heart of the department", a place not just for educational support but also a place to find community. In this role, I wore multiple hats: a librarian for the course reserves, a proctor for our testing center, a tutor during understaffed hour, and most importantly: a friend at the front desk. I was honestly spread a little thin, but bringing my heart into the job drove me to persevere. Putting work into building an inclusive community for those who struggle with loneliness and new challenges-- this was work I was doing for myself, as much as others.

At LCC, I've gotten to know professors as peers, rather than professors. One instilled a valuable tidbit of knowledge: that there exists major gaps in communication between PhD holders and students. While professors have navigated the challenges of higher education to build long-term careers, their students often struggle with the material in ways the professors haven’t experienced. More prominent with adult learners who spent years in the job market (something many professors are woefully unfamiliar with). This shaped my teaching philosophy as a STEM Tutor at Academic Achievement Center. I was quite frankly a horrible student, but that means I spoke their language of struggle and grit. I take an "imperfection" approach to instruction-- that even I will get things wrong sometimes and will need to Google things.

Tying things together, I landed my final part-time job

Interlude: Decisions

I was in job search desperation when I first moved to Eugene, that didn't really stop after landing three PT jobs. I was still in the search for the coveted full-time offer, and was also on the fence in moving again for greener pastures. I'm grateful that that offer came later rather than sooner

item.title: Landing Page
item.dc:creator: anthonyhua
item.content:encoded:
Anthony Hua
Born in Los Angeles, California

Welcome to my humble site!

This is a project website for course LIS 640 - Web Development, taught by David M. at UW-Madison. The goals of this class is to learn the methods and tools for creating/maintaining secure and interactive web content.

Why this course?

My reasons for taking this class is numerous:

  • I bought a domain name years ago with the intention of building a vanity site to host my writing. I took a summer to learn the basics of HTML and CSS, but it turns out I am not as intrinsically motivated as I thought I was, so taking this class for credit towards my Master's is a great incentive to get started!
  • My two main work backgrounds are rooted in supporting information-seeking behaviors. At UW-Madison's Libraries, managing internal documentation for our student employees is a huge component of my job. In addition, I thoroughly enjoy meticulously crafting study guides for students when I worked as a professional tutor. Using skills learning in this course, I hope to make the most well-designed and accessible wikis and knowledge bases!
  • A librarian with a STEM background is hard to come by in the job market, and I'd like to lean into that as I'm building skills.

Planned Content

  • About Me, Career Journey, and Resume for my vanity site
  • Any additional pages for course assignments
  • A section for my Mom's Recipes, for the final project

item.title: About Me
item.dc:creator: anthonyhua
item.content:encoded:
Born in Los Angeles, my parents got me and my twin sister at a bargain-- a buy one, get one deal! We are best friends to this day, but also opposites in every way: me the idealist and her the pragmatist. It was our difference that helped us understand the values of balance; the importance of learning from people who carry different perspectives than yourself.

My parents came from a family of Buddhists. While religion was not a huge part of our lives, they still raised us in an environment imbued with compassion and kindness. This is reflected in all our chosen professions: my older sister works as a child therapist, my twin sister is a teacher, and me an (aspiring) librarian.


As a kid, I grew up biking circles around my grandma's backyard in Rosemead. I watched movies like The Goonies, and was always jealous of these kids having bike adventures in the woods, with no parental supervision. I dreamed of a childhood like that, but it was impossible in car-centric sprawl of LA suburbia. I have relocated a lot since, and every move has been inspired by this love of bikable infrastructure and proximity to nature.

Places I've Lived

Redlands, California

I attend the University of Redlands for my undergrad, where I received a Bachelors of Science in Chemistry. I am grateful to had the opportunity to do a research project on the topics of environmental chemistry and microbiology. This involved spending a semester in the east Sierra Nevadas, collecting glacial samples and studying watersheds.

The city of Redlands itself is a desert-y suburb right at the very edge of the LA basin. It has a charming downtown that introduced me to the notion of supporting local businesses. Being seated at the foot of the San Bernardino mountains means there was ample hiking and camping close by!

Eugene, Oregon

After college, I visited my best friend in Eugene and immediately fell in love with the city. Moving there was a very abrupt, very risky decision. Started off unemployed, I three jobs, all related to my field of interest! I simultaneously worked at a community college resource center, a public library, and a tutoring center. I attribute the hard work I did here to kick-starting my career in higher education and libraries.

Eugene is notable for the Willamette, a river spanning length of a 13-lane highway, that splits the town in half, and phenomenal bike infrastructure that connects pedestrian life. While developing quickly, the city has remained committed to protecting its strong urban boundaries. Because of this, it is nestled between miles of dense state forest, making it a prime location for outdoor activity of all kinds. The state has the highest amount of missing persons for a reason!

Madison, Wisconsin

Currently, I live in Madison, working full-time at the University of Wisconsin - Madison Libraries. My roles are aplenty: evening and weekend building supervisor, circulation support, student coordination, desk scheduling, and (soon) reference support. I've also recently started the Masters in Library and Information Studies here at the University.

The city of Madison should win a reward for "most interesting place that the rest of the country doesn't really know about". The city is home to the state capitol, a major four-year university, and a charming downtown, all stuffed on a narrow strip of land between two lakes. Also notable are the phenomenal parks, and the extensive bike trail converted from former railway. Its because of this that League of American Bicyclists has labeled Madison one the most bikeable cities in the US

item.dc:creator: anthonyhua
item.content:encoded:
I've always been a narrative-driven person. It's a sort of love language of mine to hear the the coming-of-age stories of those who lived the equivalent of decades in single years. As a self-compassion practice, I've been attempting to see my own life in the same light. While romanticizing your life can feel a little pretentious, doing so gives a sense of purpose you cannot find anywhere else.

Describing every career-driven decision I've made without discussing the emotional and personal hurdles that inspired those decisions would leave too many gaps in the story. So to give the full picture, here is a rundown of defining roles I've held, along with hardships and character moment that shaped the trajectory of my career.

Redlands, California

They say college is a place where you plant seeds. While at the University of Redlands, I planted three. Social pressures pushed me to pursue STEM. Originally, the plan was to do pre-med with a double major in Biochemistry but was humbled pretty quickly into just a Chemistry degree. I still enjoyed the challenge and even got the opportunity to do a research project on the topics of Environmental Chemistry and Microbiology.

Being a person who wears my heart on my sleeve, I've was more drawn to my extracurriculars. I was heavily involved in Students Together Empowering Peers (STEP), a mentorship program that helped first-gen students of color transition into college and adult life. It was here that I learned the concept of "look for the helpers": that resources are always available and that we have a responsibility to guide those who were never taught how to find them.

During my Junior year, I landed a student gig at my university's library. I was hoping for a chill desk job to give me time to catch up on homework. I ended up finding a community. Among the team was my friend Will. While I was the boy scout that got promoted to Student Lead, he was a bit of a scoundrel-- initiating shenanigans at the front desk and leaving notes in the stacks as riddles for us to solve. He would often talk people's ears off about his dreams of being a librarian with a side gig of being a famous screenwriter. He would pull us aside and make us read the things he drafted. Despite being trouble, he was adored for his char; his antics got me through the latter half of college. However, Will tragically and suddenly passed in November 2020. The legacy of his wit and heart being passed on to those that knew and loved him.

Interlude: Pandemic

I graduated in 2020. Globally, nothing of note happened during this time. Utilizing my Chemistry degree, I briefly worked at as a Lab Analyst in a small water testing company's Microbiology Department. I learned I was not a great bench chemist, breaking beakers instead of "Breaking Bad".

Being cooped inside have me plenty of time to reflect. I thought about my time in Redlands and the three seeds I planted: the challenges that came with STEM, the purpose derived from mentorship, and the community that flourished in libraries. I thought about Will. I still don't quite know how to make

Eugene, Oregon

Very abruptly, I decided move to Eugene, OR in Summer of 2021

Things changed when I landed a part-time job for a Instructional Support at Lane Community College (LCC). The goals in this position was the rebuild a new iteration of STEM Resource Center that catered to the needs of students returning from years in online learning. The vision we had was to serve as the "heart of the department", a place not just for educational support but also a place to find community. In this role, I wore multiple hats: a librarian for the course reserves, a proctor for our testing center, a tutor during understaffed hour, and most importantly: a friend at the front desk.

At LCC, I've gotten to know professors as peers, rather than professors. One instilled a valuable tidbit of knowledge: that there exists major gaps in communication between PhD holders and students. While professors have navigated the challenges of higher education to build long-term careers, their students often struggle with the material in ways the professors haven’t experienced. More prominent with adult learners who spent years in the job market (something many professors are woefully unfamiliar with). This shaped my teaching philosophy as a STEM Tutor at Academic Achievement Center, a role that helped redefined how I saw STEM. I was quite frankly a horrible student, but that means I spoke their language of struggle and grit. I took an "imperfection" approach to instruction-- that getting things wrong is just part of the learning process.

Tying things together, I landed my final part-time job at an On-Call Library Assistant. There was no distinct revelation, except that it was an incredible wholesome community to be a part of. As an on-call, filling in gaps meant that I get to pair up with a lovely cast of individuals, each with their own pathway to where they were today.

---

Eugene represent a period of time where I was learning the values of investing into others. The city had a lot going for it, like the biking infrastructure and proximity to nature.

However, this was a decision I was making for others rather than myself. Another friend of mine needed support and I had made a decision to put Grad School on hold to be there for them, compromising on a promise I made to myself. But it was a huge gamble, especially given the fact that I did not have a job lined up. I faced housing scarcity and challenges adjusting to a new town. But I eventually found work that kept me busy. Putting work into building an inclusive community for those who struggle with loneliness and new challenges of adulthood-- this was work I was doing for myself, as much as I was doing for others.

I was honestly spread a little thin, but bringing my heart into the job drove me to persevere.

Interlude: Decisions

For a long time, Eugene was a difficult place to be. I was in job search desperation, which didn't really stop after landing three PT jobs. I was was always in the search for the coveted full-time offer, even if that meant relocating again for greener pastures. Greener pasture did come, but right were I was standing. Almost like a right of passage, I found life got better as I gave more attention to my community. And almost like a right of passage, as soon as life got better, I get two full-time job offers for identical roles. One at the University of Oregon, an opportunity to remain in a city to be with a community I invested so much time and care to. And another was at the University of Wisconsin - Madison, which offered tuition reimbursement for that Grad School program I always promised myself, but was 2000 miles away.

It felt as though the choice given to me years ago had circled back into my life again. A choice for others or a choice for myself. When I phoned my old supervisor (now friend) from Redlands, she told me "for once in your life, be selfish!"

Madison, Wisconsin

A year later, Summer 2024 I finish my annual review as a Circulation Specialist at University of Wisconsin - Madison, and I have started a Masters degree in Library and Information Studies. A decision I can proudly say I am making for myself.
